\f1\b0\fs18 \cf0 When SuperCollider runs a program, it first examines the code to ensure that syntax and grammar are correct. In general, syntax describes how words are spelled and grammar describes how words are formed into statements and expressions. For example, are all variable names and/or keywords spelled correctly in a program? Are statements terminated by semi-colons? \
\
If errors of syntax or grammar are found, SuperCollider writes a notification to the transcript window. Such messages\
\
\'a5 ERROR: Parse error\
   in file 'selected text'\
   line 1 char 2 :\
  4,\'a5 \
-----------------------------------\
\'a5 ERROR: Command line parse failed\
nil\
\
are descriptive but terse, so learning how to read error messages is a useful skill.\
\
